@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About — Propane Driver</PageTitle>

<div class="about-wrap">

    <section class="about-hero">
        <h1>About PropaneDriver</h1>
        <p class="about-tagline">Driver first. Everything else second.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="about-card">
        <p class="about-lead">The first version ran on a napkin.</p>
        <p>
            Not literally — but close. It was a text file on a beat-up phone, opened with a
            file manager, scrolled through at red lights. Customer addresses, tank sizes, gate
            codes. The company app had been crashing since October, dispatch couldn't explain
            why, and nobody seemed especially bothered. The drivers were bothered.
        </p>
        <p>
            After a decade behind the wheel of a propane bobtail — eight winters, 4&nbsp;a.m. starts,
            tanks that refuse to fill in the cold — the frustration finally had a name. Every
            piece of industry software had been built by people who had never been forty stops
            into a twelve-hour day, trying to find the service entrance of a warehouse that
            isn't on any map. It showed in every screen, every tap, every workflow designed
            for a dispatcher sitting at a desk instead of a driver sitting in a cab.
        </p>
        <p>
            So this got built instead. Not in a dev shop. Not with a product roadmap or a UX
            committee. It was built in the margins — between shifts, at kitchen tables, in the
            cab waiting on a customer who was running late. Every button is where it is because
            a gloved hand needed to find it fast. Every screen shows what it shows because it
            might be read by the light of a truck's overhead dome at six in the morning.
        </p>
        <p class="about-closing">
            This isn't enterprise software with a driver mode bolted on.<br />
            It's a driver's tool, full stop.
        </p>
    </div>

</div>
